- Memory is initially fragile. It is through the process of consolidation that causes this "cementing".
- Consolidation takes place during sleep and rest.
- Emotion enhances consolidation. The amygdala is activated, which in turn, activates the hippocampus.
- A self-relevant event guarantees our close attention and thoughtful processing.
- It is this processing after an event that is akin to rehearsal (working memory).
- Emotion influences what as well as how well we remember an event, "narrowing" our attention, while other aspects of the event are overlooked." id="Emotions"> <mxCell
